t of his regime's dependence on the United States and his dreams of transforming Iran into a world power. Saikal argues that, despite the Shah's early achievements, his goals and policies were full of inherent contradictions and weaknesses and ultimately failed to achieve their objectives. Based on government documents, published and unpublished literature, and interviews with officials in Iran, Britain, and the United States, The Rise and Fall of the Shah critically reviews the domestic and foreign policy objectives--as well as the behavior--of the Shah to explain not only what happened, but how and why. In a new introduction, Saikal reflects on what has happened in Iran since the fall of the Shah and relates Iran's past to its political present and future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh  aAnglo-Iranian Treaty (1857).  aAnglo-Persian Oil Company.  aArab nationalism.  aAtlantic Charter.  aBP (British Petroleum).  aBaghdad Pact (1955).  aBaku oil fields.  aBengali movement.  aCarter, Jimmy.  aChina.  aConstitutionalists.  aDepression, Great.  aEconomist.  aEgyptian Revolution (1952).  aEisenhower Doctrine.  aFirst Exploitation Company.  aFranklin Book Program.  aFriendship Treaty (1972).  aGreat Britain.  aGulf Oil Company.  aHaile Selassie.  aHelmand River.  aHorn of Africa.  aIndian subcontinent.  aIndo-Pakistani war (1965).  aIranian-Soviet Treaty (1921).  aIrano-Soviet oil company.  aIricon Group.  aJohnson, Lyndon Baines.  aJordan.  aKashmir.  aKhuzistan.  aKurdish secessionist movement.  aKuwait.  aLeague of Nations.  aLebanon.  aLiteracy Corps.  aMahshahr refineries.  aMardom.  aMobil Oil Company.  aNasserism.  aOil Law (1957).  aOman, Sultanate of.  aPahlavi dynasty.  aPalestinian i